<subSubSection id="0AB42FB28218F3139E80F2D2C301F801" pageId="16" pageNumber="242" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="42117C398218F3139E80F2D2C301F801" blockId="16.[151,1437,1488,1946]" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">
<emphasis id="70DAA02B8218F3139E80F2D2C02EFA71" bold="true" box="[199,315,1488,1514]" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">Remarks.</emphasis>
At first, we identified the specimens above as representatives of a new species and prepared a description. However, when we studied the recently published book by 
<bibRefCitation id="263F01C88218F3139DA7F2F6C5AAF995" author="Padilla-Gil, D. N." box="[992,1215,1524,1550]" pageId="16" pageNumber="242" refId="ref10664" refString="Padilla-Gil, D. N. (2019 a) Nuevas especies de Rhagovelia, Microvelia, Buenoa Registros nuevos de otros heteropteros de Colombia (Gerromorpha, Nepomorpha, Leptopodomorpha). Editorial Academica Espanola, Beau Bassin, 242 pp." type="book" year="2019">Padilla-Gil (2019a)</bibRefCitation>
, it was possible to identify our specimens as 
<taxonomicName id="85AE07BA8218F3139F87F11BC349F9A9" authorityName="Padilla-Gil" authorityYear="2019" box="[448,604,1560,1586]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Microvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="242" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fantastika">
<emphasis id="70DAA02B8218F3139F87F11BC349F9A9" box="[448,604,1560,1586]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">Mi. fantastika</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is noteworthy that the pronotum of this species was misinterpreted by the author as almost completely covering the dorsum of the thorax, except for the lateral metathoracic triangles, when it in fact it covers the mesonotum, but leaves the metanotum exposed (
<figureCitation id="DA9560BC8218F3139DB0F162C55BF9E1" box="[1015,1102,1632,1658]" captionStart="FIGURES 36–39" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1791,1815]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,182,1766]" captionTargetId="figure-17@12.[164,1424,181,1767]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 36–39. Microvelia fantastika Padilla-Gil, 2019; male from Panamá. 36–37, dry specimen. 36, Dorsal view. 37, Ventral view. 38–39, Wet specimen. 38, Dorsal view. 39, Ventral view. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4691662" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4691662/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">Figs 36</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="DA9560BC8218F3139A1DF162C5B0F9E1" box="[1114,1189,1632,1658]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–43" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1603,1627]" captionTargetBox="[164,1416,200,1573]" captionTargetId="figure-22@13.[164,1423,181,1579]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 40–43. Microvelia fantastika Padilla-Gil, 2019 from Boyacá, Colombia. 40–41, Male. 40, Dorsal view. 41, Ventral view. 42–43, Female. 42, Dorsal view. 43, Ventral view. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4691666" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4691666/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">40, 42</figureCitation>
). The metanotum was mistakenly interpreted as a posterior lobe of the pronotum by 
<bibRefCitation id="263F01C88218F3139D2BF186C559F905" author="Padilla-Gil, D. N." box="[876,1100,1668,1694]" pageId="16" pageNumber="242" refId="ref10664" refString="Padilla-Gil, D. N. (2019 a) Nuevas especies de Rhagovelia, Microvelia, Buenoa Registros nuevos de otros heteropteros de Colombia (Gerromorpha, Nepomorpha, Leptopodomorpha). Editorial Academica Espanola, Beau Bassin, 242 pp." type="book" year="2019">Padilla-Gil (2019a)</bibRefCitation>
. This species was previously known from 
<collectingRegion id="806AB2DB8218F3139F6FF1AAC07DF959" box="[296,360,1704,1730]" country="Colombia" name="Cesar" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">Cesar</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="806AB2DB8218F3139FD9F1AAC0F9F959" box="[414,492,1704,1730]" country="Colombia" name="Narino" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">Nariño</collectingRegion>
departments, respectively in northern and southwestern 
<collectingCountry id="3AB93CA98218F3139A22F1AAC5C2F959" box="[1125,1239,1704,1730]" name="Colombia" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">Colombia</collectingCountry>
. The new records above are the first from 
<collectingRegion id="806AB2DB8218F3139FF4F1CEC382F97D" box="[435,663,1740,1766]" country="Colombia" name="Boyaca" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">Boyacá Department</collectingRegion>
, in the central portion of the same country, and from 
<collectingCountry id="3AB93CA98218F3139B4FF1CEC471F97D" box="[1288,1380,1740,1766]" name="Panama" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">Panama</collectingCountry>
. The specimens from Boyacá were collected in the Palagua swampy complex (
<emphasis id="70DAA02B8218F3139D9CF1F2C521F891" box="[987,1076,1776,1802]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">ciénaga</emphasis>
), both in the swamp itself (
<figureCitation id="DA9560BC8218F3139B28F1F2C1A1F8B4" captionStart="FIGURE 63" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1838,1862]" captionTargetBox="[187,1401,903,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-81@20.[187,1401,903,1813]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 63. Palagua swamp (Ciénaga de Palagua), Vereda Muelle Velásquez, Puerto Boyacá, Boyacá, Colombia, where Microvelia fantastika Padilla-Gil, 2019 was collected." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4691686" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4691686/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">Fig. 63</figureCitation>
) and in two adjacent lakes (
<emphasis id="70DAA02B8218F3139FAEF017C35EF8B5" box="[489,587,1813,1838]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">jagüeyes</emphasis>
) (
<figureCitation id="DA9560BC8218F3139C25F016C3A0F8B4" box="[610,693,1812,1839]" captionStart="FIGURE 64" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1033,1057]" captionTargetBox="[241,1345,181,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-22@21.[241,1345,181,1009]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 64.Artificial lake (jagüey), Vereda Muelle Velásquez, Puerto Boyacá, Boyacá, Colombia, where Microvelia fantastika Padilla-Gil, 2019 was collected." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4691688" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4691688/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">Fig. 64</figureCitation>
). The Palagua swamp is a lentic water system directly connected to the Magdalena River, whereas the lakes are artificial structures built for water storage. The samples were associated with aquatic vegetation in the lakes and with the dominant hydrophytes (
<taxonomicName id="85AE07BA8218F3139D91F05EC47EF8ED" authority="(Mart.) Solms" authorityName="Solms" authorityYear="1883" baseAuthorityName="Mart." box="[982,1387,1884,1910]" class="Liliopsida" family="Pontederiaceae" genus="Eichhornia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Commelinales" pageId="16" pageNumber="242" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="crassipes">
<emphasis id="70DAA02B8218F3139D91F05EC5D1F8ED" box="[982,1220,1884,1910]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">Eichhornia crassipes</emphasis>
(Mart.) Solms
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="85AE07BA8218F3139ED0F083C05DF801" box="[151,328,1921,1946]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Pistia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="16" pageNumber="242" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stratiotes">
<emphasis id="70DAA02B8218F3139ED0F083C05DF801" box="[151,328,1921,1946]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="242">Pistia stratiotes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L.) in the swamp.
</paragraph>
